value.10: Former Royal Magician Vangerdahast to King Azoun IV of Cormyr was once an accomplished adventurer of high fame. One reason he became popular in wizardly circles was his creation of the Adventurer's Robe. Mages have always struggled with the limitations placed on them by the ability to cast arcane magics. These robes give the mage an edge in surviving encounters with melee fighters by being able to absorb some damage from hits.

value.0: A shrine to St. Fanal; although a priest of Ilmater dedicated to alleviating suffering, he believed that knowledge of the past would limit suffering in the present, and that educating oppressed peoples would expand their opportunities and capabilities. Thus he devoted himself to learning, preserving, and teaching history and those who follow his path have come to leave many tomes of various historical accounts and medical knowledges.

A shrine to St. Liwan, whose teachings focused on food and diet and the peaceful effect they had on people. His followers would not only feed the hungry; they insisted on providing the best food possible as a means of bringing satisfaction from want. Liwan believed that even war could be eradicated if all people everywhere were well-fed. In effect, those with donations of food have piled them along his likeness.

A shrine for the Sisters of Saint Jasper of the Rocks. An all female order, these monks work towards Ilmater's goals while holding agendas focused towards childbirth and medicine. The members of this order try to personify St. Jasper, an Ilmatari midwife who opened many orphanages in war-torn areas of Faerun. She became known as "of the rocks" after dieing a martyr's death, stoned by Loviatar's follwers.
A shrine to Saint Dionysus, Ilmateri patron saint of wine and spirits. Here, the locals have left donations of alcoholic beverages for travellers and the local clergy.

A shrine to Saint Amahl. He was the Ilmatari saint of nomads, especially those who wandered the desert. The Friary of St. Amahl was a caravanserai-turned-monastery in the Calim Desert of Calimshan, named for St. Amahl. The monks believed their well would never run dry "while St. Amahl watches over us."

This well made scimitar was crafted during the Interregnum and still functions exceptionally, even though the civil war ended a few years ago.
The scimitar shares some similarities with the longsword and other slashing blades, but the severity and thickness of its curve clearly sets it apart.
This well made longsword was crafted during the Interregnum and still functions exceptionally, even though the civil war ended a few years ago.
The longsword is the weapon most commonly associated with knights and their ilk.  There are many variations in the blade, but all are approximately 35 to 47 inches in length.

A holy symbol is the physical focus for the manifestation of a god's will.
Garlic is well known as a herb for flavoring foods and treating heat stroke among the preasantry. It is also used to repulse vampires.

As a follower of a specific deity there will be rites and practices associated with that deity. One thing that is common to all is the requirement to use the appropriate holy symbol when calling upon the deity's power. 

The Holy Symbol for each deity may be different and should be obtained from the appropriate temple. The holy symbol for a ranger or druid may be somthing sacred to the caster rather than a church sanctioned object.

This book contains a list of spells for which a practitioner must have a Holy Symbol equipped. 

In addition there are some spell which require other components. These are usually found in the same places arcane magic users obtain components.

This book is useful for Clerics, Druids, Rangers and Paladins.

This book was a somewhat famous writing by an Ilmatari Painbearer, but was so old that his or her name was no longer attributed to the methods contained therein.

In this tale, a child with scuffed knees cries out in pain. Hearing this, the Painbearer suggested the use of a simple herb often recommended for treating heat-illness: humble garlic. By treating bandages with this essential substance, one could accelerate the normal course of recovery from injury. Most consider it a staple tale of Ilmater's priests easing suffering for any and all.

Creating Bandages:
Add a Hand of Garlic and Rags items into your Crafter's Box, and use the Combiner on the Crafting Box. Your check will be modified by your healing skill and relevant backgrounds or proficiencies. Each attempt will cost 2 gold.

Use: Bandages can only be used on unarmored creatures who are not in combat.
The Triad consists of three deities well-known in Tethyr. They were Tyr the Maimed God, god of justice; Ilmater the Broken God, god of suffering; and Torm the True, god of duty.
This old silver mirror is of great quality. It have esoteric uses.
